The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe I should.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite advanced and our operators offer virtually all services as their Western European partners.
But there's something missing here -- a virtual operator that would make the classics cheaper.
He may not be gone for long.
We've written many times on Mobil.cz about the Czech operators being among the most expensive in Europe.
Moreover, this was confirmed by the OCTs, which pointed out that the price of SMS is higher in our country than in the rest of the Union.
The latest steps taken by the European Commission in the field of roaming charges may lead to a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there's no competition that really wants to fight.
It may sound paradoxical, but we have three mobile networks and a penetration rate of over 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to gamble that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
The chairman of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ) Pavel Dvořák has often called on them to do so, saying several times in the past that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is probably true that a traditional operator with its own network seems to have little chance (otherwise, it would be hard to find frequencies).
But there's another option - a virtual operator.
The very entry of virtual operators into the mobile market brought about a significant price reduction to which the traditional operators also had to react.
And even before the launch of Tesco Mobile and Virgin Mobile, voices in the UK sounded like ours.
But it turns out that there is a place for these operators to be, and they can be, really successful.
Besides, we don't have to go too far for examples.
In February of this year, we informed you of the launch of the mobile operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just six months, this operator has managed to gain over 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the country.
The Bank is a publicly traded company, and is a publicly traded company.
The advantage of virtual operators is that they can focus on a more specific target group.
In order to operate efficiently, they require far fewer customers than a conventional operator.
They do not involve relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
In the world, virtual operators are usually described as low-cost - offering inexpensive calls and SMS, but often balanced by a narrower range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half the price of its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, even a bet on an unharmed target group can be a pretty good bet.
This operator is specifically targeting men.
"The right guys choose Mobilking - an operator they like and can trust", says David Seibertz, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which operates the virtual carrier.
It's hard to say if a concept like that in Poland could be caught up in our country.
Vodafone press spokesman Miroslav Čepický disputes this: 'The Czech market is relatively small for the segment approach on which most virtual operators are based.
Moreover, it is relatively saturated in terms of service offerings.'
In the Czech Republic, there's no chance, mobile operators say.
But it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual mobile operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic negotiations do not look very hopeful.
Rather, Mobilking will be launched in other countries of our region", said Jana Studničková, press spokeswoman for the financial group Penta, in a telephone interview with Mobil.cz.
It has thus indirectly confirmed that the existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not inclined to this idea.
Rather, it tries to make sure that no potential competitor emerges.
GTS Novera has long been interested in launching a virtual mobile operator, which would like to take the next step towards becoming a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the field of enterprise customers.
"We are keen to offer our customers not only fixed but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly discussed this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
We have already made progress with some of them", says group press spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
Maybe it's looking forward to better times.
From the unofficial information, it seems we should expect the first virtual operator by the end of the year.
But for now, its emergence is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
'At the moment we do not believe that there is room for a full-fledged virtual operator on the Czech market.
The Czech market is very specific compared to other markets.
So far, no entity has contacted us with a complex and serious project in this area", Vlastimil Sršen of the press department of Telefonica O2 told Mobil.cz in his statement.
Other operators also rely on the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile press spokeswoman Martina Kemr adds, in a rare line with O2's statement: "We have not yet seen any viable and mutually beneficial business project to build on".
He adds: "By the end of the year, there will be no virtual operator on the T-Mobile network.
We should have a concrete agreement on the table by now to be able to consider this short-term".
Vodafone is focusing more on meeting the requirements of its own 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepický comments: 'We are open to working with potential virtual operators, especially in the area of cost-sharing and infrastructure.
That's what we consider the most beneficial for our customers.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared mobile high-speed internet network.'
Responsible authorities - One-handed with operators
The move by mobile operators is easy to understand, the entry of another operator would increase competition, lead to a decrease in prices and thus to a decrease in profits.
Why, then, should we make it easier for such a competitor to enter?
The fact that operators can pull a rope when they want to is also evidenced by the drag around the U: background.
Probably the greatest pressure on the TPP was at the time of the U:phone from T-Mobile.
The publicly available information on the OCTs website is a witness to this.
But now it's U:fon that's a good argument for not allowing a virtual operator.
In this respect, Martina Kemr pointed out: 'The competitive environment of the mobile market has been further strengthened recently by the entry of a fourth mobile operator.
In view of the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that the entry of another player would place high demands on it and, in particular, on its services.'
However, given this approach of mobile operators, the total disinterest of the Czech regulators is directly shocking.
This is not just the attitude of the CTU, which unfortunately in the Czech Republic - unlike the UK and other developed countries - does not have the power to interfere in competition.
These are exclusive to the Office for the Protection of Competition (OPCW).
But he took his typical approach to the whole issue.
'The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible after the conclusion of a contract between the mobile operator and the virtual operator for the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such contract has been concluded so far, as the potential bidder offer was probably not sufficiently interesting for the traditional operators,' stated Kristián Chalupa of the EEAS's External Relations Department in response to our question.
The comments made by the operators' representatives in this way are not surprising.
This is more than a consideration from the Authority, which is to represent the interests of consumers and, inter alia, ensure that no one abuses their market position.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "In the overseas countries where virtual operators are common, we can see that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices for mobile services".
However, it is clear that the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the fall in prices are not in the interests of the EEAS.
In fact, the shocking thing about the whole case is the emotional agreement of the three mobile operators that comes from their reactions.
The question of whether it's really just a coincidence is all on its own.
Like the absolute price of gasoline at the gas stations, it is certainly just a coincidence and a fierce competitive struggle.
'The Authority has not found any signs of anti-competitive conduct in this case and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position and therefore does not have an adequate increased responsibility for their market behaviour.
The telecoms regulator is also likely to lack the necessary tools to open up the mobile market for virtual operators,' Chalupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of dominant position in the market is one of many points of contention.
The Commission has therefore considered that the Commission should be able to assess the compatibility of the measures in question.
