We've met him on a few similar occasions.
Unfortunately, the recent Telecommunications Act did not allow the extension of the powers of the CTU to the field of telecommunications competition, although a number of experts have promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the WHSR must know better than they do, but their interests are obviously elsewhere.
It's what happens when no one's watching
The functioning of some pseudo-virtual operators, which exist in Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
They are companies that issue their own mobile phone pricing services, but they are only partially public.
They are usually multi-level marketing companies.
Their own mobile phone services are offered by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The prices of these companies are usually only for the chosen ones.
The magic is that the company is acting like a classic corporate customer to the operator who orders a large number of SIM cards.
As a significant customer, he will then receive special offers (and more).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
"If the cases you are talking about occur, they could be a breach of contract terms that we are dealing with and could result in the termination of cooperation with the company", Martina Kemr answered our question on this issue.
However, it is highly unlikely that such activity would not be carried out by the responsible people of the mobile operators.
In particular, for the three companies mentioned above, thousands of customers could be lost.
None of the operators will be able to prevent such a procedure.
These companies have substantial profits from their activities and, unlike the actual virtual operators, do not threaten them with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický points out the potential problems: "The law allows for similar speculation, but only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
They must also accept that the SIM card on their phone is not registered and therefore cannot be used in full as regular customers of mobile operators.'
But that's what it should be, at least weird.
In addition, another question arises for the OHIM.
If mobile operators are blind to a similar procedure, why are they blocking the emergence of a virtual operator?
It must be added that the Authority has a fairly strong authority to disclose such an activity and, if it does not wish to, it is not obliged to satisfy itself with the explanation from operators that they have no idea of such an activity and that their business conditions prohibit it.
When we're not the most expensive
As the text has stated several times, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has led to a marked decline in the prices of services.
In virtually every country where virtual operators have emerged, traditional operators have tried to prevent them from emerging.
The arguments they used were practically the same - too small, or perhaps too saturated, market, quality of service problems, etc.
But in developed countries, it was at this point that regulators intervened, protecting not the interests of mobile operators but their customers.
Whether through formal measures or informal pressure, they have succeeded in creating the first virtual operator and bringing in new ones.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are throwing the whole case away like a hot potato.
