The Sudetes wanted a referendum on the United States
The Sudeten Germans in 1945 demanded that the Schuymawa be incorporated into the United States.
It comes from a letter that's in the collections of the South Czech Science Library.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want to live at least under the patronage of the United States of America.
In 1945, a group of Sudeten Germans reportedly turned to the president of the United States for such a wish.
This is the result, among other things, of a letter that was kept in a private archive and is now in the collections of the South Czech Science Library.
The Germans from the Czech Krumlov request in a letter from the US president not to allow the return of the "Sumav parish" - taken by Hitler under the Munich Agreement - back to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation correctly and we want to be sure that American troops are coming to German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators", says the letter, signed "The people whose fate lies with Schumacher".
Because joining Czechoslovakia supposedly gives Sudeten Germans - knowing the Czech national nature - only hope of brutality, recklessness, misunderstanding, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter of the American president ask that he take over the protectorate over Shumava for now and forever.
"We cannot believe that, regardless of the opinion of a quarter of a million people, you would cede this territory to a foreign state that oppresses and repels minorities and has done nothing, nothing, to contribute to the Allied victory", the letter says.
The authors' inability to sign is allegedly due to fears of the vengeance of the "Czech oppressors".
If the president of the United States is supposed to doubt the views of the Schumacher Germans, it would be enough for the Schumacher County to hold a referendum on whether its citizens want to become part of the United States or live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text of the letter may sound a little naive in today's knowledge of postwar history, some scholars say that it fits the expectations of the Sudeten Germans at the time.
Although the Czech Germans had at least the slightest idea that they would be expelled from the republic, few of them accepted such a possibility.
Some expected the United States and Britain to negotiate some sort of autonomy for the Sudetes.
Others believed they would simply stay in Czechoslovakia.
This is confirmed by the famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in the Czech Republic.
