Even rats have feelings
When rats or cockroaches run from danger, does that mean they're afraid too?
Neurologist Joseph LeDoux believes that many animals have feelings, too.
But how could we know if they feel the same way when they behave like us?
For years, the online magazine Edge has been publishing contributions from well-known scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents a selection of answers to the question "What do you believe to be true without being able to prove it?"
I believe animals have feelings and other states of consciousness that I or anyone else has ever been able to prove, when we can't prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case, we can at least hope, because all human brains have the same basic configuration.
But once we start to focus on another kind of thing and open up to questions of perception or general consciousness, we're entering a disagreeable field because the hardware doesn't match.
When a rat is in danger, it does what many other animals do: it pretends to be dead, runs away, or attacks.
People behave similarly, which some scientists judge to be comparable subjective experience.
I don't believe that, though.
Two aspects of the brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to that of animals.
This is partly because circuits associated with human consciousness almost always involve the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its role in short-term memory and executive or control functions).
This vast area is significantly more developed in humans than in other primates, and it seems to be completely absent in other creatures.
At least in those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including knowing who we are, and the ability to plan and make decisions, there is reason to believe that humans are different even from other primates.
Another dramatic feature may be the linguistic nature of man: Because so much of his perception is connected with language, it is often said that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, we could rule out animals.
But even if the consciousness of language were not important, it would certainly be influenced by language, so the animal consciousness, however constructed, would probably differ from most states of our consciousness.
So it's hard to tell what consciousness looks like in other animals.
When, as something internal and subjective, it cannot be measured or analyzed, because of the special hardware, based on our own experience, its exploration puts us in the middle of big problems.
Most of my conclusions relate to the content of conscious experience, but there is another aspect of consciousness that should be scientifically accessible.
It would be possible to study processes in the consciousness of animals regardless of their content, and that's exactly what happens in short-term memory studies in primates, especially in the example of visualization.
But this approach, which was developed by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, focuses more on neural correlates of consciousness than on causal mechanisms: they may be identical, but they may not be.
Interestingly, this approach also highlights the importance of the nonfrontal cortex for visualization.
What does that mean for feelings?
I'm inferring that an emotional system, like a fear system, is activated in the brain consciously by its own activities.
So what we call "fear" is a mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of the brain's defense system (or its effects, like bodily reactions) uses operational memory.
Viewed from this angle, the senses are closely related to the areas of the cortex that primates, and especially humans, are characterized by.
In connection with the nature of language, there is a subtle graduation of perception, because we can use words and grammar to distinguish and categorize states, to attribute them to others, alongside ourselves.
For example, Antonio Damasio believes that feelings arise from more primitive activities in the cortex and brain stem that are dedicated to bodily sensations, similar to Jaak Pankseep, which focuses more on the brain stem.
Since this network has not changed much over the course of human evolution, it could easily have played a part in the feelings felt by several animal species.
I cannot, in theory, dispute this, but I consider it unprovable.
Pankseep argues that what we think of as fear in rats and humans is likely to be the same for both organisms: But how can we verify, Pankseep goes on to say, that rats and humans feel the same when they behave similarly?
The cockroach flee danger - does he feel fear?
In my view, the mere similarity of behavior cannot prove the similarity of experience.
True, the neural comparison moves us further: rats and humans have similar brain strains, but cockroaches have no brains.
But is the brain stem responsible for feelings?
And even if it were possible to prove it in humans, how would we want to prove it in rats?
I think rats and other mammals, maybe even cockroaches (who knows?), have feelings.
But I really don't know how to prove it.
And because their feelings are probably fundamentally different from ours (because human consciousness is based on special circuits and language), I'd rather study emotional behavior than rat emotional perception.
In any case, we can expect to see progress at the neural level if we measure the same in rats and humans.
Just as I don't study the language and the consciousness of a rat, I don't study the feelings, because I don't know if they exist.
It may seem shortsighted, but I'd rather move forward than throw myself against the wall over and over again.
I'm a practical emotionalist.
