The debate on bilingualism: immersion in English
In this edition of Focus on Education, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi will discuss candidates' stance on bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, a California academic and director of education at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is co-author of "Better Than You Think: Why the Middle Class Needs to Choose Schools".
Effectively reaching out to Hispanic voters is a tricky matter.
Barack Obama's education agenda is just proof.
The Obama campaign claims that "African-American and Hispanic students are significantly less likely to attend college than white students", which is true.
To combat these performance disparities, the Obama education agenda specifically promotes, among other things, "transitional bilingual education" for those who are just learning English.
The question for Barack Obama, however, remains whether his commitment to bilingual education, which emphasizes the use of languages other than English in the classroom, is stronger than his interest in reducing performance disparities.
Take Sixth Street Prep, a charter elementary school in the East Los Angeles area.
The students at this school are in the vast majority of cases Hispanic from low-income families.
More than a third of the students, many of whom have recently joined, are just learning English.
Yet in 2008 the state math test had an incredible 100 percent of fourth graders.
Almost as amazingly, 93 percent of fourth-graders passed state tests in English language and literature.
This incredible achievement was achieved by a different method than Obama's preferred one.
Sixth Street emphasizes control and practice, continuous assessment of ability and unjustified access.
And, as Obama should note, according to Linda Mikels, principal of Sixth Street, the school's pedagogical approach to those who are just learning English is "full immersion".
The immersion in English emphasizes the almost privileged use of English in teaching.
Ms. Mikels, who is against bilingual education, told me, "We had a tremendous success with one totally new student from Mexico -- you'd walk into a classroom in 12 months and never know who he is".
"It works", she said, "it works for us".
Would Obama take the school as Sixth Street Prep as a model for what other schools with large percentages of Hispanic and English learners should look like?
The results the school is achieving should make the answer to this question self-evident, but the education agenda of its own party (the National Education Association has long been a supporter of bilingual education) and its own consistent support for bilingual education obscure the prediction of Obama's answer.
While Obama agrees that immigrants should learn English, he recently trivialized the matter by saying that people should stop worrying about "English-only" laws.
Instead, he said, "you should make sure your children speak Spanish".
If Obama really wants to erase performance differences, he should think carefully about the educational patterns that work, rather than ridicule and trivialize them.
