Gebreselassie, 35, set the 26th world record in his career, which is truly incredibly broad - he's surpassed the world record or at least he's the world champion in every distance from the metric mile to the marathon.
Last month Gebreselassie skipped the Beijing Olympic Marathon because he feared - perhaps too scared in hindsight - that air pollution would irritate his asthma problems.
Instead, he promised to run to Berlin.
In almost perfect conditions - sunny and 48 degrees at the start, 55 degrees at the finish line - Gebreselassie won on Sunday with a lightning average of 4 minutes and 43 seconds per mile.
As track runners like Gebreselassie and Paul Tergat of Kenya focused on the longer course, the marathon record for the past decade has dropped by more than two minutes since Brazil's Ronaldo da Costa won in Berlin in 1998 with a time of 2:06:05.
After Sunday's victory, Gebreselassie told reporters that he had a hip spasm two weeks ago and missed a week of training.
