Askalefa Magarsa of Ethiopia finished second in 2:21:31 and Helene Kiprop of Kenya finished third in 2:25:01.
The pride and obstacles of black life in a segregated city
Hidden among the sprawling amusement parks of Greater Orlando, miles away from all the glitter, noise and gigantic, lies a quiet city that is alive with the pride and the hardships of African-American life.
Eatonville, the first entirely black city to be incorporated and where Zora Neale Hurston spent her childhood, is no longer as simple as it was described in 1935: "a city of five lakes, three croquet courts, three hundred brown skins, three hundred good swimmers, plenty of squash, two schools, and no prison".
It's a pilgrimage site now.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to the annual Eatonville Festival of Dawn! to pay tribute to Hurston, the most famous female writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
The city she described remains a sideline, even though she made it a stopover for tourists by including it in a Florida tour guide created by the Federal Writers Project during the economic crisis.
It is still as independent, dignified, and private as it was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted and did not share their true feelings with a white man who "knows so little about us that he doesn't even know what he's missing".
Even today, in the year when the black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, calls for an open discussion of race, many locals remain cautious of foreign views.
"We pay close attention to how our story is told", says 59-year-old Hortense Jones, who has lived here since birth and is a member of the city's oldest parish.
"It must be right".
Eatonville has long been characterized as a paradox of triumph and effort.
It's both a historical model of black upsurge and a community of nearly 2,400 people where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is a center of literature, but also a shadowy example of the Southern rural black culture - sometimes despised, sometimes praised - that originated from American slavery.
It is not surprising that the inhabitants here are both proud and protective.
And the concern about the idea of Eatonville really started with Zora, which is the only way to call Hurstons here.
She introduced her hometown to the world through heartfelt books full of proverbs such as Mules and Men (1935) and Their Eyes Were Watching God (1937).
Five paragraphs of the Florida Tour Guide transformed the city into a little bit of Highway 17, which leads through the often-overlooked center of Florida, into a stage of black history and human drama.
With a big drumming in life and literature, Hurston led readers to the store of the first mayor of Eatonville, Joe Clark, and then turned to more personal places.
"On the left side of the road", she wrote, "is a white, brown-decorated modern national school with well-maintained courtyards and playing fields, always cared for by Howard Miller, though he is not very literate".
She also mentioned Dash's widow's new husband and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells all kinds of drinks and anything that fits a watch hotel".
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston linked Eatonville to self-government, but also to illiteracy, marriage rejuvenation, and sex.
This obviously wasn't the typical Fodor's publishing house.
It wasn't really a portrait that everyone would appreciate.
"The dawn said it like it was", says 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of the Johnson girls, whom Hurston made immortal by quoting men who sang silly songs about their beauty.
"Some people didn't like it", she added.
Hurston is still remembered here as a cypress fairy who often returned after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Augustus Franklin, 77, recalls that most of the time she came to town, she arrived unannounced in a huge Chevrolet, smoking and wearing trousers in a city that is still proud of decent dress.
Most of the population was fascinated, Franklin said, but many were disgusted.
"The people of Zora always loved to see", Franklin said.
But, he added, she is rocking on a chair on the back terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, "never staying too long".
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were being withdrawn from print.
It seemed that Eatonville had forgotten her, along with the rest of the world.
Although she was once a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes, and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she had previously lived.
There were no major mourning ceremonies or large public readings in Eatonville.
"I don't think they understood its significance to the world or its message at all", said Valerie Boyd, author of Hurston's 2003 biography Wrapped in Rainbows.
The change came in the 1980s.
Orange County officials wanted to extend the city's five-lane highway instead of Kennedy Boulevard, the local two-lane highway.
The Orlando spill has already pushed Interstate Highway 4 through the western edge of the city.
The proposal came at a time when Eatonville was still recovering from a complex historical period.
Forced integration, among other things, ended the relatively idyllic isolation of this community.
In the 1950s, the fight to mix racial hatred reached the threshold of the community.
"At that time, a bunch of white boys, they came and threw oranges and stuff at the people who were sitting on the side", Franklin said.
"We actually had a lady here that was killed.
They threw the melon out of the car".
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston challenged the Supreme Court's demand for forced integration and declared its decision in Brown v. Board of Education "offensive to my race rather than celebratory".
Residents now claim that the desegregation of schools, while positive in some areas, has diminished cohesion in Eatonville and undermined the courage of the youth.
"Black children were used to hugging - I remember - you hugged your teacher in the morning, you hugged your teacher in the evening", said N. Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins and executive director of the nonprofit group Preserve the Eatonville Community.
It took until the teachers and students came from the same place, she added.
"You don't embrace your white teacher because your white teacher - I mean there's a cultural barrier", said Miss Nathiri.
Civil rights, however, helped to make room for many other Zora Neale Hurstons - black writers, actors, and artists who, like her, rose above prejudice with slight confidence and quotes such as "How can anyone deny the pleasure of my presence!
I don't understand that".
In 1975, Alice Walker set off to Hurston's unmarked grave and began fighting to revive her reputation.
Five years later, Hurston's acclaimed biography by Robert E. Hemenway was brought to the bookstore shelves and re-recorded in the American canon.
The highway project came just as Eatonville's most famous daughter was rediscovering the ramp lights.
Her former Hurston neighbors now regarded her as a savior.
To show what could happen to their highway, the community began planning Hurston's Festival in 1988.
Thousands of fans arrived for the inaugural event two years later, and many return to the celebration every January.
The state has withdrawn from the highway proposal after years.
"These five highway currents have resuscitated, you would say directly, real civic pride", said Nathiri.
Boyd said it simply, "Eatonville was saved by dawn".
The victory over the highway project helped change the city's image.
Outsiders like Rachel Munson, a lawyer who started attending the church in 1993, began to appear in greater numbers, and residents began to reevaluate the past.
Eatonville was added to the National Register of Historic Places in 1998.
A new one-story library (named after Hurston, of course) opened in 2006 on the re-paved and embellished Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains a Florida anomaly: just six miles from downtown Orlando can sometimes act as a summer rainy alley, as small as when it was founded with only 27 black families in the 1980s.
(Today, 90 percent are black.)
With strangers coming to look for the story and meaning of Eatonville, it's still often treated with caution.
Permission is required for most interviews, and certain things -- like murals in the oldest church in Eatonville, painted by white people and showing blacks in the fields -- are not allowed to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Jones, a bold, confident teacher who likes to eat red, still fear that their isolated community will not be properly understood.
And as the Hurston Festival grew, so did the pride of the home.
Young people in particular tend to see Eatonville as Hurston saw her entire race: beautiful, troubled, and so on, but not better, not worse, and just as proud, creative, hardworking, stupid, and diverse as other American races and ethnicities.
Franklin's nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, voices a sincere love for the community as he plans to return to Eatonville after college to work for the local government or police, which he says would benefit from some help.
And even younger ones, like the 11-year-old twins of Winter Park, Alondra and Alexia Kenon, seem to have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"Most people, just walking through this door, think, 'Hmm, this town is nothing against the others,'" Alondra Kenon said recently after church on Sunday.
"But if you really stop and look at history for a moment, it's a very nice city".
We all speak fluent financial terms here in New York.
At first glance, nothing has changed.
If tourists in Manhattan had stayed away from the newspaper booths and the huge TV screens in Times Square, they wouldn't have realized they were in the middle of a storm.
They would never guess that in a glass-filled beehive of offices above their heads every day, the bankers and investment fund managers who monopolise New York City have their worst "bad day at the office" since the 1929 crisis.
The cops keep rocking metal carriages down the hallways and carrying muffin bakers to the breakfast meeting.
Hispanics keep moving between the towers, carrying like human mullas, fifty iron shirts hanging from the pendants on their backs.
Office rats are still in line for their morning bagels at the street food stalls, and it's still impossible to get a yellow cab on a weekday between 4 and 7 p.m.
It didn't seem like a crisis at all until, with all the talk of pessimism, I decided to set up a savings account on Thursday afternoon.
Even though I timed this assignment to cover the late afternoon shift at my local branch of JP Morgan Chase, there were already about 20 people in line.
Not in front of the cash registers to collect or store cash, but in front of the checkbook, where older customers order cheque books, tourists ask for a way to Macy's mixed-use store, and new customers set up accounts.
Most of the people before me, as I learned from Starr, my "licensed personal banker", came for the same reason I did.
But they've already taken their savings from smaller banks in places they came from, like New Jersey, Pennsylvania, or Staten Island.
They have taken money from so-called thrift stores (slightly similar to building savings), money associations and types of savings stores that operate in only one state and claim to care for their customers like a family.
In the past 15 years, such banks have quietly gone bankrupt.
A few days ago, Washington Mutual, a $327 billion bank, went into bankruptcy, and when New Yorkers were coming home for the weekend on Friday night, another bank, Wachovia, with $440 billion in assets, was trying to catch a buyer.
The office and retail workers who stood in front of me, fearing another collapse, were moving their cash to a bank that is seen as a safe haven and that does most of the savings on Wall Street.
The average New Yorker has learned a lot about finance in the last week.
A woman at my local Chinese supermarket was on the phone talking to Lehman Borthers, that bankrupt bank, and her thin top executive, Dick Fuld, with such familiarity as if she were making fun of a lazy colleague.
And Lyn, my uniformed 50-year-old housekeeper, changed the subject of our usual conversation - Brad, Angelina, or my food delivery.
After my visit to the bank, she said, "I have my savings in money market funds now.
I moved it, I'm not taking any chances".
