The Blood That Is Sure Again
HEMA-Québec celebrated its 10th anniversary yesterday and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, was rightly pleased that HEMA-Québec had become one of the most reliable and efficient blood suppliers in the world.
Above all, he has regained public trust, which was severely shaken by the contaminated blood scandal of the 1980's and 1990's.
As is common knowledge, the national blood reserve administered by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Board was contaminated with the HIV and hepatitis C viruses during the 1980's.
In view of this drama and the wave of public displeasure, the Canadian Government launched a public inquiry in February 1994, chaired by Judge Horace Krever, to explain the circumstances leading to such a tragedy and to formulate recommendations that such a disaster should not happen again.
While Judge Krever waited to submit his report, some provinces launched a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, this task was carried out by the Géline Committee.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were established in Canada: Héma-Québec, which was to host Québec, and the Canadian Blood Society for the Supply of All Provinces and Both Territories.
"When Héma-Québec began its activities in 1998, only 38 percent of the population still trusted the Quebec blood system", recalls Dr. Décary.
"The situation was depressing.
Through continued efforts to increase blood safety and steady work in this area over the next few years, we have regained public trust", he says, adding that by the beginning of 2008, Hémé-Québec was trusted by almost 94% of Quebec's population.
However, Dr. Decary does not lose sight of the fact that "trust is something very fragile".
Since its establishment on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
"We saw many cases of the human form of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, then in Europe", relates the woman who has led the company since its founding in 1998.
"And we didn't know if the disease could spread through blood.
We therefore based one of the basic recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports, that in the event that we do not know and that there is a risk of spreading serious disease, in this case, Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by brain degeneration that inevitably leads to death, exclusionary measures should be taken.
So in April 1999, we refused blood from people who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
Then, a few years ago, it was safely proven that the disease is blood-borne.
So this episode showed us that it made sense to be cautious".
In 1999, a much more accurate HIV detection technique appeared on the market: nucleic acid tests (NAT) that allow the presence of the virus itself to be directly detected in the donor blood rather than the antibodies on which previous tests were based.
NAT tests have shortened the gap between the time the patient is infected and the time when our techniques can detect the first viruses in the blood, explains the specialist.
We've been able to shorten this time to less than a week.
We've significantly reduced the risk that some donors could be infected without knowing it and without us being able to find out.
This improvement has significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS through blood transfusions.
One in 12 million people today is at risk of getting HIV-infected blood.
"In other words, it means that before someone gets HIV, 12 million blood products will have to be distributed.
Since Héma-Québec distributes 400,000 to 500,000 blood products a year, it will take 24 years for the first case of HIV transmission via blood products to appear.
I believe that today we can get or prescribe blood transfusions for healing in complete peace", says the head of the management of Hema-Québec.
"The challenge for the next decade is to keep our products safe.
We never know what kind of disease or fetal element may appear in the system.
Just last year, the chikungunya virus was discovered on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted into the bloodstream by insect bites.
There is a need to be constantly vigilant,' continues Dr. Décary, stressing that in addition to safe supply, Héma-Québec must also expect sufficient supply.
"The demand is growing as the population ages.
As a result of more aggressive cancer treatment, patients often need a new dose of red blood cells or platelets.
The aging population is also affecting the blood donor network, which on average only comprises 3% of Quebecers eligible for donation".
Every healthy person is at least 18 years old, according to the eligibility criteria, but can donate blood only once every 56 days, that is, six times a year.
On average, 14 percent of people who donate blood are not accepted because they carry AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have visited a country where they are treated for muddy cold, they are excluded for one year.
"With these 3%, we can maintain a state that meets the needs of hospitals.
The shortcomings are very rare.
However, the members of the donor network need to be supplemented in proportion to their age and inability to donate blood.
However, it is difficult to persuade people to donate blood, especially to keep them and encourage them to become regular donors.
Life is so messy these days that we rarely find an hour to donate blood", says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products but also human tissue, such as bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin, which is almost exclusively used for major burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before they are deposited at Hema-Québec, which also operates the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The cord, formerly considered biomedical waste, is a blood vessel rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"A few weeks ago, we celebrated the deposit of our thousands of spinal cord blood samples into the bank, and we expect to collect over 1,000 a year.
Early next year, we should start offering them for transplantation", explains Dr. Decary, who describes the cord blood collection program as a popular one.
"Some mothers are disappointed that they don't have access to it", because Hema-Québec doesn't have enough funds to offer this complex and expensive program to all Quebec hospitals.
