Opinions - Orwell's speech by Barrick Gold
In the 17 September issue, Le Devoir printed a letter from Patrick J. Garver, Executive Vice President of the Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
It confirms, with Orwell's logic, that the world's largest gold producer has launched a lawsuit against three authors and a poor small publishing house for insulting honor to provoke a "transparent public debate" and demands six million dollars.
If it's true that judges are independent and impartial, they don't judge the truth, especially in the case of a lawsuit of honor, but the law.
It's no surprise that Garver is completely oblivious to this fundamental distinction.
Or is it the best way for Barrick Gold to conduct a public debate to bring to justice anyone who dares to defend a position that is contrary?
Whatever the outcome of the trial, the authors and publishers of Noir Canada will be forced to spend decent sums to prepare to defend and fight a highly unbalanced battle against the army of lawyers backed by the almost unstoppable pockets of the mining industry.
The tactics of these unbalanced battles, moreover, often consist in the liquidation of defendants in order to impose conciliation proceedings which will silence the parties and, moreover, frighten anyone who dares to take up the matter.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it had to present its view of the whole thing to the public.
Contrary to what is happening in several countries where Barrick Gold operates, in Canada, debate is usually about exchanging ideas, not about punching a bullet.
So it was not enough for the subcontractors to open their books, their documentation and to start a real debate through newspapers, media, publications and funding independent scientific teams that could shed light on the whole thing.
But Barrick Gold seems to have no confidence in public opinion and has been clamoring for rejection of petitions and letters in support of the authors of Noir Canada.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he can demand "public debate" while contemptuously denying the public's views?
In the vice president's world, it seems that the word only refers to the fat-paid lawyers, not all Canadians; it's a rather narrow concept of the term.
In a democracy, even the nationalists have a say.
Barrick Gold does not understand - or does not want to understand - that the public that supports the authors and publishers of Noir Canada is doing so primarily because it rejects the brutal ways of the mining industry.
The public is ready to hear Barrick and assess the matter, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, not in what many perceive as a prosecution that is meant to be a "public debate" prosecution (Barrick has, by the way, just issued an official appeal to the authors of Noir Canada to officially announce that they should stop using the term...).
Not to mention Garver's surreal speech, the Barrick Gold-initiated prosecution is a direct attack on the university's freedom to seek and seek truth, which is essential to any democratic society.
It generally rejects the right to quote reliable sources and to debate the facts and interpretations which constitute the basis of intellectual activity.
If in a country like Canada, it is impossible to study and discuss topics that are not liked by the wealthy companies of this world without repeated prosecution, who else can do it?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could have created it if it followed the scientific standards used by the authors of Noir Canada.
He has a right to an answer.
The university environment we belong to has long been able to manage debate and disagreement and resolve conflict.
Barrick Gold's overcharged lawsuit makes it clear that despite what he claims, he has no desire to conduct a transparent debate.
It's a loss to the university world, as it is to the public debate in Canada, and it's time for governments to put in place measures to limit this kind of unlawful prosecution.
Operation to save Wall Street - Democrats and Republicans agree
The Bush administration and congressional leaders, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the largest economic bailout since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
A new version of the plan to use $700 billion to stem the financial crisis that has been raging on Wall Street for months has yet to be approved by both houses of Congress.
It provides in particular for better control by elected representatives over its application, new mechanisms to ensure the repayment of public money deposited, new measures to capture the number of houses seized for non-payment and the right to monitor the salaries paid to the managers of rescued companies.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, House Speaker Nancy Pelosi and Republican negotiator Senator Judd Gregg announced the good news yesterday, minutes after midnight, after the two-day marathon of negotiations had ended.
"We have made great progress and reached an agreement that will be effective in the markets", said Bush administration spokesman Henry Paulson.
"Everything has been done to ensure that the real economy and ordinary Americans are safe from the crisis that is happening on Wall Street", the Democrat explained.
"This is a crucial point: if we don't, the trauma, chaos and disruption of American daily life will be enormous", Republican Judd Gregg declared.
In the last few hours, the negotiations have been at full throttle for fear of the effect of another failure on investors' sentiment.
The deadline was to open the markets this morning.
Both candidates for U.S. president were invited to negotiate later and both expressed their preference for the deal, but failed to express their dissatisfaction with the need to resort to such an extreme solution.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has agreed to supplement the agreement with some measures, notably one designed to allow homeowners to stay home, and measures to pay state-run employers to rescue firms.
"When we ask taxpayers to take special measures because of the irresponsibility of some people, there is no point in congratulating.
But these measures are necessary,' he explained on TV.
His Republican opponent, John McCain, who was asked by another station whether he would vote for the proposed plan, replied: "I'd like to see the details, but I hope so".
"The rough traits I read [indicate] that this is something we all have to digest and move forward with.
Choosing to do nothing is simply unacceptable", he said.
The goal of the $700 billion plan is to buy back doubtful claims and risky and unsold assets of U.S. financial institutions with taxpayer money.
The plan comes after 14 months of a crisis triggered by a bubble in the real estate market that first led to the collapse of subprime mortgages, then moved to other, more widespread forms of loans (PCAA) and resulted in a freeze of cash and the collapse of banks and financial institutions.
The Republican lawmakers are concerned about the failure of last week's first draft agreement.
Ever since Democrats agreed that some of the "toxic" assets of troubled companies would only be guaranteed by the government, but not bought, there has been a belief that the hopeless situation is being ignited.
In an attempt to bring the contrary views together in Congress, a measure was added to provide that the government will be able to introduce new fees to help it recover its deposit if it has to bear losses for five years as a result of the programme.
The new plan includes a first deposit of 250 billion, to which an additional 100 billion can be added if the President deems it necessary.
The additional $350 billion would have to be approved by Congress in a new vote.
In return for his help, Washington will get a stake in the rescued companies, which will pay him dividends on the profit and which he will be able to resell when it's all over.
The Federal Government will have the possibility to delay the foreclosure procedures for the loans covered by the plan, as well as to set limits on the amount of valuation and compensation paid to the managers of the companies affected.
The plan's backers would like to put it to a vote in the House of Representatives today and the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all efforts, it is still unclear whether their plan will be green.
Yesterday, votes continued to rise against the project in both the Republican and Democratic camps.
"It's quite obvious that Washington is not listening to you", said Scott Garrett, a Republican member of the House Finance Committee, to voters.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
However, paying the taxpayers is not the answer.'
Democratic Rep. Brad Sherman, moderator of the congressional group called the "Skeptics Committee", presents the whole thing differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred respected economics professors, including three Nobel laureates, have written to us: we ask Congress not to rush too much and carefully consider the way forward", he said yesterday.
At the same time, the crisis was reaffirmed in Europe as a global one.
Following the end of the extraordinary meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of Fortis Bank Group for EUR 11,2 billion (USD 16,3 billion).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it was withdrawing from the purchase of its competitor, which has been on the verge of bankruptcy since losing EUR 2 billion ($2.9 billion) due to the risky credit crisis in the US real estate market.
Fortis employs 85,000 people, is one of the 20 largest European banks and one of the 10 largest insurers.
"We will not lose this money", said the Dutch finance minister Wouter Bos yesterday.
"In return, we get the right to vote in the bank and influence.
