Psychology of trumps: Why are we spending more money?
In auctions, customers are willing to spend more money, overvalue goods.
The neurological and economic underpinnings of this well-known - and seemingly irrational - behavior have been uncovered by researchers in neuroscience and economics at New York University.
According to their study, published in the journal Science, people don't want to be left behind in eBay auction competition, so they'd rather pay too high a price.
Researchers used experimental auctions to try to map the pattern of this "game" in the nervous system.
One group of volunteers bet, the other group took part in a random auction, where the active brain areas of the subjects were examined using functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI).
In both games, participants could win money, but in the auction game, where the important element is to beat the other side, the entire subcutaneous tissue called the striatum began to work intensively when the loser lost.
This brain area plays a role in the "self-reward" mechanism of the nervous system, among many other functions.
The price scratches can therefore be explained by the researchers as an attempt to avoid a sharp reaction of the striat.
To support their theory, a financial cross-sectional survey was carried out by members of the research team from a number of economists.
In this case, three groups bid against one partner under different conditions.
The control group was simply told what the fair value of the product concerned was and they made bets.
Additionally, other group members were promised another $15 reward if they came out of the game winning.
The third group received $15 before the auction, but in the event of a loss, its members lost that money.
The difference between the two groups was, therefore, that one group was emphasized as a winner and the other as a loser.
However, members of the "loser" group were willing to go higher than the control and "winner" group, as confirmed by the neurologist's hypothesis.
"These results cannot be inferred from any previously existing economic theory.
They have thus far explained the phenomena observed at auctions of joy of winning and risk-avoiding.
It was only when neurological imaging methods helped us resolve the contradiction between the two theories that we now came to the third explanation", says Andrew Schotter, a professor of economics at New York University.
Hepatitis: when should I see a doctor?
About half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infections, and in Hungary, chronic liver disease is listed as a leading cause of death.
The number of domestic hepatitis infections is estimated at 100,000, but only 7,000 are cured, because the sick often do not know they are infected.
The name hepatitis is a synonym for infectious liver damage caused by various viruses.
Their symptoms are very similar, with inflammation of the liver and jaundice being the most common, but the causes and the diseases they cause are different.
Depending on the cause of the disease, hepatitis virus is spread in two main ways: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (e.g. infected food, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses in the blood and body fluids (sperm, urinary tract, saliva).
In any case, travellers should protect themselves by vaccinating against A and B viruses, there is no vaccine against C viruses.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating an infected food, usually accompanied by nausea, weakness, stomach problems, and vomiting.
Then, the skin and eyelids will develop yellowing, light stools, and dark urine, which can take two to three weeks to treat.
Every year, a million people worldwide die from a more serious form of the disease, liver cancer and cirrhosis of the liver caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason is that only one in ten infected people is estimated to be medically cured.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if left untreated, it can lead to cirrhosis of the liver or liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know that the cause of the disease is liver cells that are destroyed, and in many cases the first symptoms do not appear until 20 to 30 years of age.
Therefore, timely prevention, regular monitoring is very important.
The disease is much more common in three groups than the average: among people who had a blood transfusion before 1991, among drug users, and among people with tattoos.
Currently, the estimated global number of people infected with the chronic hepatitis C virus is 200 million.
Since the disease can be demonstrated by routine laboratory tests, a person should consult his or her doctor if he or she experiences any symptoms of unknown origin.
If detected early, the disease is treatable, the virus can be removed from the body, preventing infection and preventing cancer.
30 September is World Hepatitis Day, which was first organised globally by organisations representing the sick in 2004.
It aims to raise awareness of the chronic hepatitis caused by these viruses, the causes of its occurrence and the importance of early detection.
