To copy the complex eye function, engineers went after the idea of a laser rangefinder.
It shall identify obstacles up to 2 metres in front of the BR23C in a 180-degree field of view, calculate their distance and send a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which shall be immediately converted into a collision avoidance operation.
The obstacle is captured within a fraction of a second, then the robotic car begins to mimic the movements of the bee and rotate the wheels to the extent necessary to prevent a collision, immediately changing direction.
Unlike any existing system, this maneuver of evasion is carried out in a completely instinctive manner.
"If it wasn't for that, the robotic car would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles", explains Toshiyuki Ando, director of the Robotic Car Mobility and Project Lab.
It must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology fits the most vulnerable and innermost layer of the safety-protective packaging, inside which the impact is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what the bee does to avoid other bees.
This process must not take longer than a blink of an eye.
However, unlike bees, this movement cannot be upward, downward or even evenly distributed, it can only be two-dimensional and only in the direction in which the wheels can be rotated.
Instead of the endless options offered to bees in avoiding them, only the rotational motion, acceleration and deceleration were used in the case of the robotic car.
BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and have higher energy density, meaning they have a longer lifetime than lithium-ion variants.
Ando says instinctive, intelligent responses are important, not the ability to process, much less the ability to store data.
This mechanism must process and respond only to a few incoming signals per second.
It doesn't need to store and respond using intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, so it only uses memory of a few kilobytes in size all the time.
It doesn't need a memory with a gigabyte or a megabyte capacity.
This is the first step towards developing a technology for immediate avoidance that Nissan estimates could reach mass-produced vehicles within 10 years.
Another possibility may be to connect the unit to a GPS satellite navigation system, which would guide the driver to the assigned final destination after avoiding obstacles in the road.
