Finance Minister Henry Paulson said of the compromise: "The programme will work and be effective, but further steps need to be taken".
The written form of the package was published before the opening of Asian markets on Sunday at 8pm CET (i.e. Monday at 2am CET), but no particular increase in the markets was caused.
The draft law, called the Emergency Economic Stabilisation Act 2008, to be established by the programme, will be voted on by the House of Representatives on Monday, followed by the Senate.
President George W. Bush spoke to Pelosi on Saturday night, and then the news of the deal was welcomed by the White House.
"We are pleased with the progress made overnight and greatly appreciate the efforts of both sides to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy", said White House spokesman Tony Fratto.
The program differs from the original Bush administration proposal, which was to have a total of $700 billion spent on the repurchase of low-quality mortgage-backed securities at once.
Now, it's possible to spend up to half of the $700 billion in the first round, so that $250 billion will be spent immediately after the expected Congress decision on Monday, and the Treasury will buy securities backed by mortgages that are rated as low-quality, and the fate of the remaining $100 billion will depend on the president's decision.
The programme shall be supervised by a special committee, including the Chairman of the Federal Reserve.
The allocation of the second half of the $700 billion will depend on further Congressional decisions.
The Ministry of Finance may, within the meaning of the Act, use a combined tactic: it may simultaneously redeem non-performing loans, mortgages and securities backed by mortgages, or other 'toxic' loans.
The purchase can be made through auctions or directly, the competent officials of the Ministry have said.
The legal standard will allow the companies concerned to participate in an insurance programme in which the Ministry of Finance provides them with a guarantee of funds of concern, in return for which the companies pay a price corresponding to the expected damage.
As Henry Paulson said, the law provides the necessary resources to spend up to $700 billion to meet the urgent needs of the U.S. financial system, whether it be large-scale purchases of bad funds, insurance of bad funds, or to prevent the systemic risk of collapsing some of the major financial institutions.
"We will take the necessary steps to be ready to implement the law as soon as it is signed", he added.
Bankers who are in trouble and waiting for government assistance, on the other hand, can expect the government to cut their fees - simply called "the golden parachute" in slang.
The Commission has therefore concluded that the aid granted by the State to the beneficiary is compatible with the internal market.
The restriction essentially means that if the Ministry buys in the auction, a tax surcharge will be imposed on the gold parachutes unless the fallen bank directors are sent directly to retirement.
