Open Office, we have the third edition of the anti-Microsoft package.
It's the day of Open Office.org 3.0, an open source personal-generation package that aims to reach more and more users, from home to office, from professionals to public administration, as a free alternative to the more well-known Microsoft Office.
After about a year of volunteer work, controlled by SUN Microsystems, the new Open Office is showing up to the general public with various new features: adding more, much more significant ones, such as compatibility with Apple's Mac OS X operating system and support for the new Open Document Format (ODF) 1.2, the latest standard ISO version, to the welcome screen and the revised and improved opening window.
The emphasis is also on collaboration with Office 2007, Open Office is able to open a document even with a new Microsoft add-on (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx).
Interesting features of some models are the ability to reduce the size of a PowerPoint presentation, useful for example for electronic transmission, or the ability to transfer a PDF file to a graphical implementation model and maintain the original page look.
Still, from this perspective, we can create "PDF hybrid" documents that look like typical Adobe graphics and have the characteristics of a spreadsheet processor or text program.
Cooperation is an element that has been greatly improved within application programs: it is excellent to work together between different users and avoid conflicts on changes, in a text program each collaborator is assigned a comment color to make the identification clearer during the revision phase.
Some companies are also working to bring some of the features of Open Office to the web (on the cloud), and they should re-create the final result in the coming weeks.
The Italian version can be downloaded at http://it.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.html, the English version has been added to the mirror since Friday.
In addition to Windows and Mac OS, the package is also available as usual for the Linux operating system.
The installation CD may also be sent to the home or workplace upon request.
And if the free-of-charge theme can be a catalyst for spreading in households, the Open Office business is a big bet, and it can already count on a variety of projects being implemented in public administration and schools.
And there is no shortage of training, consulting and support services ideal for small and medium-sized businesses, which could open up business prospects.
Open Office consists of five main models: Writer, for video writing replacing Word; Calc is a desktop processor that aims to replace Excel; Impress for PowerPoint-like presentations; Dbase, as in the more famous Access, is a program that allows you to work on databases; Draw, after all, is a graphics model.
The goal for 2008 is to reach 5 million downloads, and considering we're almost 3.600,000 today, with the release of the new version, it's possible that this number could be exceeded.
