Goodbye to the old Paradiso cinema, the city destroys historic halls
The historic movie theaters are closing in favor of the Multiplex.
"A city without a cinema is like a blind man, like a face without eyes".
The painting, presented by Giuseppe Tornator, successfully documents what is happening in the major Italian city centres, but also in the rural towns.
The process of restricting cinemas, the birth of large multisals in the suburbs and the subsequent demise of monosals in the central urban areas is one of the events that seems inevitable and irreversible, but it also has all the signs of a true cultural crime.
Often historical sites filled with memories disappear, "it's like losing a friend, a friend, a friend with whom we shared a journey and a lot of emotion", says the director of New Cinema Paradiso, a film that won the Tornador Oscar and the Grand Jury Prize at Cannes 20 years ago, and which told the poetry of a village cinema and the sadness of a way of life that cinema probably lost forever.
The values obtained by Anec, the main operator's association, are clear: in the last five years 316 cinemas of the traditional type have closed their doors, and the highest bills have been paid primarily by the halls in the most important cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 less in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 less in Palermo.
The region most affected by closures is Emilia-Romagna, which has lost 82 cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And proof that the first factor responsible for their disappearance is the rise of multiplexes is that these three regions in Italy have recorded the highest number of new cinema multiplexes: 195 films in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in both Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
'The Italian process has developed irrationally' says Paolo Protti, President of Anec, 'it is useful to create new structures, but it would be necessary to guarantee that the existing ones survive because when a cinema in the city closes, not all its visitors are willing to move into a multiplex.
Not to mention the lack of funding for the fund for operators: the previous government debt is about 10 million euros.
From a moral and ethical standpoint, it is a shame that the government does not respect the existing laws.
Between EUR 16 and EUR 18 million a year would be needed to support the sector.
The case of Bologna is interesting, the first Italian city to deal with closures and decided to find a way out by signing a protocol between the municipalities and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy to protect and promote small cinemas in both historic centers and suburbs.
The planned rules include tax relief measures for operators and public mobility benefits: spectators will be able to enter the restricted traffic zone and will be given special parking and parking rates.
I like the initiative called Giuseppe Tornatore and I hope that other cities will follow Bologna's example by introducing other measures.
