When energy is born from the waves, the big ones enter the game.
It's an infinite deposit that covers more than 70 percent of the earth's surface and is now being discovered by the world's major energy companies.
Waves, currents, tides, tides are new sources of inexhaustible energy that have been caught by the eyes of giants like Chevron, who are now trying to reach out to these sources.
The possibility of generating energy from ocean activity has been studied for over a century, and in the 1970s, in connection with the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When oil prices fell around 1980, the idea of using marine energy was abandoned, but now environmental organizations and new oil price increases gave the sector a new impetus.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London in 2007 stated that about 15 percent of the world's electricity consumption could be covered by the use of ocean waves.
This would be twice the amount of energy currently produced in nuclear power plants.
And there's also currents and tides and tides.
The giants are attacking.
The company that bet on marine energy was Enersis, which agreed in 2005 to build the facility in northern Portugal.
When this was announced, it looked like a huge revolutionary step.
After two years of betting on marine energy, more and more companies are betting on marine energy rather than traditional energy.
"Chevron is studying ocean energy technology", a spokesman for a company connected to the U.S. oil giant told the Wall Street Journal, an economic daily, "and they're thinking about working with us".
The cooperation we're considering is about getting a permit from the U.S. Energy Commission that's necessary to start a marine energy project in Alaska.
We cannot underestimate this signal, especially considering that it is in Alaska that the U.S. is still mining oil and recently President Bush came up with a plan for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey are also tracking the sea energy footprint, and the amounts invested so far, although not detailed, show a growing interest, observers say.
The technology that needs to be developed.
Experts are talking about a technology that is still in its infancy because they don't know what impact the use of marine energy will have on the environment.
For now, facilities in Portugal and some in Scotland are small and do not appear to cause major ecosystem problems.
But to produce more energy, we need to use technology with a greater impact on the medium.
The methods are different: Ocean Power, for example, uses a combat system that is interconnected.
The force of the wave moving with the buoys up and down is converted by means of coils and cylinders to the hydraulic pressure inside these buoys.
Pressure dissolves the turbine, which supplies power to the generator.
The power is being delivered to shore by undersea cables.
So far, there are four such facilities in the design phase, which are just waiting for federal approval and some of the energy could be used for military purposes.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, is already generating power for the mall and parking lot using six offshore wind turbines in New York's East River.
The movement of water during the flow and tide causes the turbines to spin, which in this rotational motion power the generator.
Verdant said they have a long list of clients waiting for the necessary authorisation for the possibility of using this energy.
After the waves, after the tide, after the tide.
The potential for tides and currents is of particular interest at this time, say the Electricity Research Institute.
